references: In our experiments, we evaluate the proposed approach using three benchmark datasets of varying complexity: Diginetica (DIGINETICA, 2016), Yoochoose  (DIGINETICA, 2016), Yoochoose (Ben-Shimon et al., 2015), and OTTO  (Ben-Shimon et al., 2015), and OTTO (Philipp Normann et al., 2023). These datasets differ in terms of the number of events and the diversity of item sets. The experiments focus on click and order events, ensuring a minimum item support of five and a session length of at least two clicks for all datasets  (Philipp Normann et al., 2023). These datasets differ in terms of the number of events and the diversity of item sets. The experiments focus on click and order events, ensuring a minimum item support of five and a session length of at least two clicks for all datasets (Hidasi et al., 2016). We adopt a temporal train/test split approach for training and testing the models. Specifically, the entire last day from the Yoochoose dataset and the entire last week from the Diginetica and OTTO datasets are designated as test datasets  (Hidasi et al., 2016). We adopt a temporal train/test split approach for training and testing the models. Specifically, the entire last day from the Yoochoose dataset and the entire last week from the Diginetica and OTTO datasets are designated as test datasets (Krichene and Rendle, 2020), with the remainder used for training.
